## DAG Anti-Patterns To Avoid

List anti-patterns relevant to DAG interpretation.

| ID                       | Anti-Pattern                                                    | Why It Is Harmful                                                                 | Corrective Principle                                                                   |
| ------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-001 | Treating traceability as prerequisite topology.                 | It can introduce false cycles or misleading ordering.                             | Include traceability-only relationships in the traceability view, not the primary DAG. |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-002 | Dropping true edges to force acyclicity.                        | It creates a cleaner graph by hiding required relationships.                      | Report cycles or use SCC condensation rather than deleting source-grounded edges.      |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-003 | Treating DAG order as implementation order.                     | The DAG represents execution-tied evaluation prerequisites, not design or execution sequencing. | Use the DAG to inform implementation, audit, and test-design planning, not to prescribe architecture. |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-004 | Treating horizontal architectural planes as topological layers. | Plane is architectural concern; layer is prerequisite depth.                      | Preserve both views separately.                                                        |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-005 | Creating synthetic nodes without justification.                 | Synthetic nodes can hide missing source meaning.                                  | Label and justify every synthetic gate or SCC node.                                    |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-006 | Hiding cycles as open questions only.                           | Cycles materially affect DAG validity.                                            | Include explicit cycle analysis and SCC handling.                                      |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-007 | Inventing edges from topical similarity.                        | Similar items may not depend on or validate each other.                           | Only source-derived or logically necessary relationships become edges.                 |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-008 | Ignoring invalid catalog groups.                                | Invalid groups can create self-edges or hide dependency/falsifiability conflicts. | Validate catalog groups before using them as DAG nodes.                                |
| EVAL-DAG-ANTIPATTERN-010 | Inventing execution artifacts for source material without deterministic IO. | It fabricates evidence that no executable source item requires. | Represent only source-explicit execution-tied facts; otherwise leave the material out. |

Add project-specific anti-patterns only if present in the source inventories.

---

## Completeness Checklist

Before finalizing this DAG, verify:

* Every required source file was considered.
* Every represented source file appears in the Source Inventory.
* Every represented dependency item has a deterministic execution tie before node creation.
* Every represented hypothesis item has a deterministic execution tie before node creation.
* Every represented dependency item is mapped to exactly one DAG node.
* Every represented hypothesis item is mapped to exactly one DAG node.
* Mixed items include only source-explicit execution-tied kernels.
* No substitute execution artifact is invented for residual prose-only source meaning.
* Invalid catalog groups are reported.
* Every source-derived prerequisite edge is represented in the primary DAG or in the traceability-only view.
* Every source-derived validation edge is represented in the primary DAG or in the traceability-only view.
* Every source-derived falsification edge is represented in the primary DAG or in the traceability-only view.
* Every source-derived machine-gate dependency is represented.
* Every edge has a direction rationale.
* Every edge has source basis.
* Every primary DAG edge endpoint is execution-tied or a justified `TBD`.
* No primary DAG cycle remains unless SCC condensation is used.
* Every cycle is reported.
* Topological layers are valid.
* Horizontal architectural planes are preserved separately from topological layers.
* Mermaid and DOT graph views are included or summarized with rationale.
* Traceability-only edges are listed separately.
* Open questions are recorded rather than resolved by invention.
* Repository satisfaction state is not assessed unless explicitly requested.
* No roadmap appears.
* No actual epics appear.
* No actual milestones appear.
* No implementation tasks appear.
* No architecture is invented.
* No tests are written.
* No evaluation result, process result, review result, release result, state label, final realization assertion, or non-execution artifact is asserted.
* The DAG is detailed enough to support downstream implementation, audit, test-design, and remediation planning without creating non-execution artifacts.
